<HEAD>Friends Pay Last Respects to Max Robinson</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 6 to correct Jackson's characterization of
conversation with Robinson about contracting AIDS, adding quote from
Jackson eulogy</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> eulogized former <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> on Friday as a man who `` would n't adjust, would n't knuckle under the face of racism.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s, delivered the eulogy at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> church where friends and co-workers of the nation's first black network television anchor paid their last respects to <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. The former anchor, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, `` would n't adjust, would n't knuckle under the face of obvious and not so obvious racism. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> had been ill for more than a year when he died Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> of complications resulting from AIDS. He was 49. `` <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> never adjusted,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` He sought to transform. He was not a TV thermometer who measured things and spilled them back out. He tried to be a thermostat _ to change the temperature.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters that he talked to <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> about how <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> contracted AIDS and that <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> told him: `` It is not homosexuality but it was promiscuity. ... Let my predicament be a source of education to our people.'' Among those attending the ceremony were ABC News President <PERSON> Roone </PERSON> <PERSON> Arledge </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON>, 60 Minutes reporter <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>. `` I think ABC News is a better place today than it was before <PERSON> Max </PERSON> was there,'' said <PERSON> Arledge </PERSON>. `` A lot of that is due to his efforts.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> began his broadcasting career as a radio station disc jockey in his hometown of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. He moved to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1965 and three years later became the first black to anchor newscasts at a major TV station, appearing on the 6 p.m. and 11 p.m. news on Channel 9 <ORGANIZATION> WTOP </ORGANIZATION>, now <ORGANIZATION> WUSA </ORGANIZATION>, with co-anchor <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> then left <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after 10 years at the top of the ratings to join <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> as the first black to anchor a network news show. He was one of three anchors at <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, along with <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>. `` He did an enormous amount for us,'' said <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>. `` He did an enormous amount, I think, for his community. ... When <PERSON> Max </PERSON> died, we all hoped he'd find some peace.'' The frustrated <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> made headlines publicly denouncing racism at the news organization during a speech at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in February 1981. <PERSON> Arledge </PERSON> was supervising news coverage when <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was an anchor, and he changed <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>' three-anchor format after <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> died in 1983. At that point, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> inherited the job as sole anchor of the newscasts, and <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was assigned to do news briefs and weekend anchor. In 1984, he left <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and joined <ORGANIZATION> WMAQ-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The following June, he entered a hospital specializing in alcohol rehabilitation suffering from emotional and physical exhaustion, according to <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON>, director of communications at <ORGANIZATION> WMAQ-TV </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Aronson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> never returned to the station, and did sporadic freelance work after that. `` I think one of my basic flaws has been the lack of esteem, not really feeling great about myself, always feeling like I had to do more,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> profile. He is survived by his mother, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, and stepfather, the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, both from <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, and four children, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>, <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> and <PERSON> Malik </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> also leaves three surviving siblings, <PERSON> Jewel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepperd </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Yancey </PERSON> and civil rights activist <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> TransAfrica </ORGANIZATION>. All live in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. There will be no private funeral, as <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s family has decided to have his remains cremated.
