<HEAD>America's Armenians Plan Somber Christmas To Commemorate Quake
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The catastrophic earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> has dampened the Christmas spirit in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Armenian community, with many festivities canceled and money normally spent on gifts being sent for relief efforts. Armenians in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as well as in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, have canceled or postponed Christmas and New Year's parties, weddings, dances, tree decorating and other activities to mourn the thousands killed in the Dec. 7 quake. `` The earthquake has pretty much ruined Christmas for most of the Armenians I know,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Atamian </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawyer who had volunteered to answer phones for the Armenian <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Saddle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` We have canceled all of the gatherings and dances and social functions. We felt it would be totally inappropriate.'' The earthquake devastated the cities of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION> and up to 100 rural settlements in northwest <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Official Soviet sources have put the death toll as high as 55,000 and estimated the number of homeless at over 500,000. Christmas is celebrated Jan. 6 by the Armenian church and Dec. 25 by Armenian Catholics and Protestants. Leaders of the two branches of the Armenian church in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declared a 40-day period of mourning when the earthquake hit. But many Armenians say the decision to mute celebrations was spontaneous. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Archbishop <PERSON> Torkom </PERSON> <PERSON> Manoogian </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, will hold a requiem Mass for children Jan. 7 instead of the Christmas party he usually holds for youngsters, according to <PERSON> Adrienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexanian </PERSON>, a volunteer at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vartan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>. About 70,000 Armenians live in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> area. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with the largest Armenian population outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> _ some 250,000 live in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area _ Armenians have canceled weddings and holiday parties. Churches are holding special requiem services after Sunday Masses. Armenian Protestants are preparing for a somber holiday. `` Of course we will still observe <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s birth,'' said <PERSON> Rosey </PERSON> <PERSON> Maranjian </PERSON>, who answered the telephone for the <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> at its headquarters in <LOCATION> Paramus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` But there is nothing to celebrate even though <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> is born.'' `` We keep asking, ` Why us?''' she said. One of her cousins died in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, she added. `` It's a sad way to celebrate such a joyous event,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Janbazian </PERSON>, the association's executive director. `` Instead of sending out Christmas cards to friends and exchanging gifts, we are sending the money to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. And most families are doing that,'' said <PERSON> Shakeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadehjian </PERSON>, a secretary in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of the Armenian <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which celebrates Christmas Dec. 25. `` Most of the people, without asking us, are canceling their wedding ceremonies'' until after the mourning period ends Jan. 17, said Rev. <PERSON> Nareg </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrikian </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apostolic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Glendale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` The first reaction among Armenians was to cancel everything, not even to decorate Christmas trees,'' said <PERSON> Ara </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalaydjian </PERSON>, editor of the Armenian Mirror-Spectator, an English-language newspaper published in <LOCATION> Watertown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The area is home to 30,000-40 ,000 Armenians <PERSON> Kalaydjian </PERSON> said he planned a quiet dinner with his family. `` We wo n't exchange gifts. We wo n't have a tree,'' he siad. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogosian </PERSON>, editor of the Armenian Reporter, said his English-language weekly, published in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, ordinarily carries announcements of holiday events. But over the past two weeks, he said, `` all the listings carried a notation: canceled, canceled, canceled, one after another.''
