<SECOND>PM-Israel-Profiles,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Familiar Faces In New Israeli Cabinet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sketches of four key figures in the new Israeli Cabinet:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, leader of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, retains his post in the new government. A former underground fighter and <ORGANIZATION> Mossad </ORGANIZATION> secret agent, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has been characterized as a politician with the tenacity of a bulldog. He has rejected any negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oganization </ORGANIZATION> and is opposed to calls for an international peace conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. But he has pledged to introduce new peace proposals after his new government is in place. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, 73, was born in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and emigrated to what was then <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> in 1938, a decade before the founding of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He has a law degree and did not enter politics until 1956. He served as prime minister in 1983-84 and again starting Oct. 14, 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> moves to the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The son of a Polish timber merchant, he arrived in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> in 1934 and as a teen-ager delivered messages on his motorcycle for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s founding father, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Gurion </PERSON>. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, 65, has written at least four books and has said that in his youth he wanted to be a poet. He is seen as an intellectual, but many Israelis also view him as arrogant and distant. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' once-dominant <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has won national elections only once in the past 11 years, and the 1983 victory was not by a sufficient margin to allow Labor to rule without <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> favors an international peace conference and has promoted the idea of a dialogue with Palestinians in confederation with <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. As finance minister, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> will have to confront growing budget deficits and major financial problems in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s industries, including companies owned by the Labor-allied <ORGANIZATION> Histadrut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> remains defense minister, a post he held when the Israeli Cabinet voted to withdraw its invading force from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> after a three-year occupation. A native of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, he was ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from 1968-73. His term as prime minister was cut short in 1977 when he was forced to resign in a scandal over his wife's illegal overseas bank accounts. He and <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> have had a long rivalry for leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, 66, fought in World War II, taking part in allied operations in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and fighting behind enemy lines. He was army chief of staff during the 1967 Six-Day War, in which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> took control of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Golan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> from neighboring Arab countries. He has ordered a firm response to the year-old <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> uprising in the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> replaces <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> as foreign minister. A native of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, he immigrated with his family to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the age of 14 and studied aeronautical engineering at the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. He moved to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1950 and is said to be proudest of the planes and missiles he designed here, both for the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military and for export. Colleagues describe <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> as cool and thoughtful. He was ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1982-83, and he is likely to be heavily engaged in dialogue with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> following the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to open talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> considers a terrorist organization. <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, 62, is an extreme conservative and reportedly turned down the job of defense minister in 1980 because he opposed the just-concluded Israel-Egypt peace treaty.
</TEXT>
