<HEAD>Legal Experts Say Crash Could Raise Liability Problems For Pan Am</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The decision by <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government not to alert the public to a fairly specific bomb threat received long before <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 crashed in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> could raise liability problems for the airline but probably not for the government, attorneys say. `` I do n't know of any legal requirement that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> go public on a thing like that other than notifying the airline involved and possibly the embassies,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawyer who specializes in aviation accident cases. `` It's a difficult area, but if the government notifies the airline in question, I think the government position is justified,'' <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said there are `` some policy reasons from the government's standpoint for not'' notifying the traveling public. One of the purposes of the Federal Aviation Act is to enhance aviation and an announcement of a specific threat which might not be bona fide could conceivably result in travelers not flying. Flight 103, originating in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with a change of planes at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, crashed in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> on Wednesday, killing all 258 people aboard and more than 20 on the ground. It was bound for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said that an unidentified individual telephoned the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> on Dec. 5 and said there would be a bombing attempt within two weeks against a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> aircraft flying from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The conduit would be an `` unwitting'' passenger who would take the device from <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and then board a U.S.-bound flight, she said. It has not been established, however, that the telephoned tip was related to the Pan Am crash. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said dozens of threats are received each day and all are taken seriously. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s counter-terrorism office, said there have been 87 calls similar to the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> call over the past three months. But the Dec. 5 call, apparently from a tipster, appeared to be taken more seriously than most others. Many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies were apprised of the threat, including the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> mission in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, where a notice of the threat was posted on a bulletin board. No word went out to the general public. The prior notification `` is going to raise an interesting question'' in connection with the other passengers `` who were not members of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> staff whether they should have received similar notice from <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a lawyer specializing in defending airlines in accident cases. <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON> said in an interview Thursday night that not enough is known to conclude that sabotage caused the jumbo jet to crash. `` We do n't know if this is a terrorist attack,'' he said. Asked what an airline's obligation is once it has been notified of a specific threat, <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said, `` It's a tough situation. ... They do n't have to stop operating or stop flying, but certainly they have a duty to meticulously inspect.'' <PERSON> Kreindler </PERSON> said that in some other instances of terrorism involving air travel, evidence-gathering in lawsuits has focused on airline security precautions. Officials said <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> stepped up security at key airports in the wake of the threat. Anyone filing lawsuits seeking settlements in excess of a $ 75,000 limit in international airlines cases would have to show willful misconduct on the part of the airline in order to be successful. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> said willful misconduct is extremely difficult to prove, carrying with it a heavier burden of proof than gross negligence. Willful misconduct is a wrongful act done intentionally or an improper act done wantonly with knowledge of the probable consequences.
