<HEAD>Official Questions ``Fairness Opinions'' to Company Stockholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has questioned the independence of financial advisers who tell stockholders a proposed leveraged buyout of their company is a good deal. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Thursday that experts who write `` fairness opinions'' often get higher fees if the deal goes through. The opinions offer conclusions on the fairness of a buyout offer. Asked by Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., whether fairness opinions were independent, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said, `` All in all, I am quite suspicious in a significant number of cases, that the fairness opinion is prepared by somebody with an incentive to go along with management `` Personally, I think that needs to be addressed.'' <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said he was giving the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee his personal opinion _ not that of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, which is currently reviewing all aspects of leveraged buyouts. Leveraged buyouts occur when investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with that company's cash flow or by the sale of its assets. <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said the commission wants to determine whether it should issue new rules to protect investors, and predicted the review would continue at least through February. Fairness opinions are primary factors in the transactions, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said, because `` shareholders accord a great degree of weight to the fact that a favorable opinion has been issued.'' The opinions usually attest that the price offered for shares of a company is a fair one. The hired financial adviser must rely almost exclusively on the limited information that management supplies about the company. Subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., said an investment bank may receive $ 1 million to prepare the opinion, but $ 1.5 million if the deal goes through `` It sounds a little bit like a kickback to outsiders,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said.
