ion on the issue. The League of Conservation Voters awarded <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> a low score, 13 out of a possible 100. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> voted according to the `` environmentalist'' position only twice out of 16 test votes. However, <PERSON> Pritchard </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> had been responsive to concerns about parks and historic preservation. The Wilderness Society expressed a split view, saying in a statement by Vice President <PERSON> Sydney </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> that though they differed on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil development, <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> `` has been accessible to the conservation community.'' Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., who has led the so-far successful fight to ban oil exploration in federal waters off central and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> `` has not stood in the way of measures to protect the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast'' and `` will bring an open mind to the issue. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> hailed <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> as `` clearly a friend of business'' with an 80 percent favorable voting record, according to the chamber's tabulation. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, is a 1950 graduate of the College of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, where he grew up and where his father served as mayor in the 1940s. He will be the second Hispanic in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Cabinet. Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> has been asked by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to stay on. `` I went to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to balance the budget and we still have n't done it,'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> once said when asked to name his biggest disappointment In