companied the Bushes during a trip to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1982. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has written or co-written more than 60 technical articles, mostly dealing with blood chemistry and diseases. He has directed national research on sickle cell anemia, a fatal blood disease that primarily affects blacks. The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> native is a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professions </ORGANIZATION>, and has often expressed concern over the low number of minorities entering medicine. At the same time, he has said that <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION>, while heavily black, welcomes white students, especially those willing to practice medicine in rural or urban poor areas. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, a 1954 honors graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and a graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, and his wife, Ginger, have three children. He is active in the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, and serves on the National Executive Board of the Boy Scouts of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
