<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON>, a surprise nominee to become the first secretary of the new <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, is a former long-time <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> congressman who lost his seat at the hands of redistricting. <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON>'s selection Thursday by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> surprised advocates for veterans groups and those who deal with veterans issues in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> because he has dealt little with issues of concern to veterans. `` I'll admit it was a surprise to me,'' said Rep. G.V. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` His name had never even surfaced.'' One congressional aide described the <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> reaction as a `` giant shock.'' <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON>, 62, did not serve on veterans committees in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and since then he has worked at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. However, initial reaction among veterans and their advocates was supportive. `` I think he'll be a strong and balanced advocate to be sure veterans get their share of whatever pie is available for allocation,'' said Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stilwell </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officer who served as deputy undersecretary of defense in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, who successfully pushed legislation to upgrade the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to a Cabinet level departm