<HEAD>Spain's Taste For American Food Boosts U.S. Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> has turned into one of the American farmer's richest overseas markets, but <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> trade analysts say the character of those shipments are changing rapidly. For example, since the entry of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> into the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports of wheat and feed grains have fallen dramatically, says the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. But other kinds of products, including many high-value items, have taken up much of the slack. In the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, the total value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm exports to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> was $ 848 million, up 30 percent from $ 652 million in 1986-87. An important factor is the thriving <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> economy, which has helped create new and expanded demand for processed or semi-processed foods that carry higher price tags than the traditional bulk commodities. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s gross national product, or the sum of its goods and services, grew 5.5 percent in 1987, the highest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and is expected to gain nearly that much in 1988, the agency said Thursday in a report. `` However, at more than 19 percent, unemployment remains the country's most compelling economic and social problem,'' the report added. The surge last fiscal year put <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> among the world's top 10 markets for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural exports. Leading commodities included: soybeans and soybean meal, corn and corn gluten feed, tallow, hides, skins, walnuts, peas, beans, lentils, seeds, yellow grease, prunes and poultry meat. Further, the report said, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> supplied all of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s imported almonds and half of its imported cattle semen. `` Increasing disposable income, a more urban and youthful population and larger numbers of working women have resulted in greater interest in convenience items, fast foods and more eating outside the home,'' the report said. `` Patronage of restaurants traditionally is high.'' The report added: `` Although the standard three-hour business lunch endures, consumption of fast foods and snacks is increasing. Numerous tourists and the growing number of Spaniards who have traveled abroad tend to encourage greater interest in new food ideas.'' As an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> member, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s food processing industry has become a prime takeover target for investment by many kinds of multinational companies, and this shows little sign of subsiding, the report said. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> makes up an important part of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s total market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural products. Last fiscal year, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipments to the 12-nation trading bloc totaled $ 7.5 billion, with <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> accounting for more than 11 percent. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was the second-largest market -LRB- and the biggest for a single country -RRB-, with $ 7.3 billion in 1987-88. Others in the top 10 included: <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, $ 2.3 billion; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, $ 2 billion; <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, $ 1.9 billion; <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, $ 1.7 billion; <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, $ 1.6 billion; <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, $ 800 million; <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, $ 700 million; and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, $ 600 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have added 1.4 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain to their 1989 granaries, including wheat sold to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> at subsidized prices. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s order announced Thursday was for an additional 1 million metric tons of corn for delivery under a recently extended supply agreement between the two countries. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> bought 400,000 tons of wheat under the subsidy program. The latest sales by private exporting companies brought total corn sold to the Soviets to almost 8.03 million tons in the agreement's sixth year, which began Oct. 1. Last year, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> totaled slightly less than 5.2 million tons. Exporters are required to report foreign grain sales of 100,000 tons or more to the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> within 24 hours. Smaller sales are reported weekly. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1 million tons of corn would be about 39.4 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.61 per bushel at the farm level, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates, meaning that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $ 103 million. Although no wheat has yet been sold for 1988-89 delivery under the pact, the Soviets have ordered 500,000 tons of soybeans and 532,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of grain sorghum. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said seven export companies were involved in the sale of 400,000 tons of wheat to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, some 14.7 million bushels having an estimated farm value of $ 58 million at recent prices The companies included: <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 90,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, 40,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Nissho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iwai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 30,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Bunge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 40,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Tradigrain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Tradecom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 30,000 tons; and <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 120,000 tons. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the sales were part of an authorized 1 million tons of wheat announced on Dec. 7 under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP. With the latest sales, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> now has 210,000 tons remaining under the authorization. The program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the bonuses due the seven exporters for the latest deal averaged $ 23.10 per ton of wheat, or about 63 cents per bushel.
</TEXT>
