<HEAD>Dollar Rises Again Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar rose Friday against the Japanese yen for the second consecutive day, while share prices closed lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar opened higher at 124.90 yen and continued to edge up, finishing the week's trading at 124.95 yen, up 0.33 yen from Thursday's close. It had gained 0.40 yen on Thursday. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 76.42-point gainer the previous day, fell 88.35 points, or 0.30 percent, closing at 29,686.26. A currency dealer described trading as light due to a dearth of news regarding exchange rates. `` The dollar may have moved up somewhat but it's nothing major because market participants are sticking to the sidelines ahead of the weekend,'' the dealer said, speaking anonymously. But on Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> Gov. <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said the foreign exchange market was stabilizing in the wake of the dollar's recent sharp decline He also said the central bank would continue to monitor the market. Securities dealers attributed the bullish <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market to stable currency exchange rates and a wait-and-see mood ahead of the New Year holiday period. `` Most foreign players seem to be out of town for the Christmas break and as a result, the whole market is slowing down,'' said a trader with a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> securities company. Another dealer said investors were trading actively ahead of the expected demise of the 87-year-old Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, who has been seriously ill for over three months. `` The market will very likely slow down when the emperor passes away,'' said the dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on con