<HEAD>South Africa, Angola Vow Continued Support For Each Others' Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> say they will continue supporting rebels fighting each other's governments, despite having signed a pact pledging not to interfere in each other's domestic affairs. Foreign ministers of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> signed the agreement Thursday granting independence to <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which will become the new nation of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> in 1991. It has been ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since World War I. The pact also stated that 50,000 Cuban troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> will withdraw, under <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervision. The signatories affirmed `` the principle of non-interference in the internal affairs of states'' and promised not to allow their territory to be used `` in connection with any acts of war, aggression, or violence, against the territorial integrity, inviolability of borders or independence of any state of southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> backs rebels fighting to overthrow <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government, and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> harbors bases of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s white-led government. <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunem </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, told reporters `` the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> is carrying out a just fight in the name of all humanity against apartheid, therefore the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> will continue to receive the solidarity and support from our government and our people.'' He denied <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is part of `` southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' saying that region encompasses only <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. But he refused to say whether the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to maintain several bases in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. At a separate news conference, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, R.F. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, was asked if his country would suspend assistance to Angolan rebels, known as <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would be telling you a lie if I say to you that we can suddenly end our friendship with <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>,'' he replied. `` We will remain sympathetic to that organization. Friendship can not be terminated in this manner.'' He promised, however, that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would not violate the accords, suggesting it will continue with political and diplomatic support of the rebels but will not send weapons. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said if the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> `` is allowed by <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to continue to operate as they've done up to now from <LOCATION> Angolan </LOCATION> territory ... to kill members of the civilian population of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, that would be a clear-cut violation of the various agreements.'' <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state who mediated talks leading to the accords, told reporters Wednesday the question of support for rebels was a matter between <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and other diplomats watched the signing of the accords Thursday. `` With the independence of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last colonial question will have been resolved,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. The agreement calls for a one-year transition to independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, beginning April 1. Under the pact, half the 50,000 Cuban soldiers are to pull out by Nov. 1, when <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> is to hold its first free elections for a national assembly. The rest must be gone by July 1, 1991. Foreign ministers <PERSON> Isidoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Malmierca </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunem </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> then signed an agreement under which 70 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers will monitor the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal. A <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence calls for about 2,000 civilian administrators and military police to back about 7,500 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers as South African troops withdraw and a civilian government is organized. The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which has fought South African forces in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> more than 20 years, was not part of the accords but said it will honor a cease-fire. Angolan guerrillas also were excluded. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has controlled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, a mineral-rich territory of about 1.2 million people, since capturing it from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in World War I. It refu