<HEAD>43rd Assembly Ends Session Of Concord, Agreements, Peacekeeping</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-UN-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reflecting the climate of detente between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION>'s 43rd <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> concluded its most harmonious session. The buoyant, sometimes tumultuous session that ended Thursday was highlighted by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s farewell, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s show-stopping debut and the assembly's decision for the first time to leave <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and travel to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to hear <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> The 12-week session adopted most resolutions by consensus including, for the first time, the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> resolution recognizing the Soviet troop withdrawal. It adopted the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> budget without a divisive note Wednesday _ the first time the financial plan was adopted without a vote since the world body was founded 42 years ago. The 1990-91 budget of $ 1.76 billion was about $ 22 million less than the last. Its adoption by consensus and the lower expenditure were viewed as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> victory. <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> president and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, told the closing session the assembly had benefited from the new international climate of detente and cooperation between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and had contributed to it <PERSON> Caputo </PERSON> said the consensus within the 159-member assembly was `` unprecedented in the history of the organization.'' The world body even charmed its most strident critic, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which committed itself during the session to repay nearly $ 500 million owed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> budget and peacekeeping forces. The money had been withheld for years for ideological, budgetary and other reasons. Relations strained during most of the eight-year <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration eased considerably and when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> delivered his final speech in September, he praised the world body for its peacekeeping and peacemaking in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and elsewhere. Before the session ended, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> played host at the signing of an agreement granting independence to <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, better known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. It was signed Thursday by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, which agreed to withdraw its 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The assembly will reconvene in mid-January to discuss financial questions and funding of a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitoring force in <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the Soviet president, delivered a tour de force of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> diplomacy at the assembly this month, promising unilaterally to cut 500,000 Soviet troops and many jet fighters in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. In December, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refused <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> a visa to address the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is an honored <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> invitee and, in protest, the assembly voted overwhelmingly to move to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to hear <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. There, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> explicitly recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, renounced terrorism, and called for direct talks with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> announced it would end a 13-year ban and open a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, changing the entire <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> landscape and opening new possibilities for peace.
