<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> is headed toward a final vote on the free trade agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that is scheduled to take effect New Year's Day. `` The U.S.-Canada free trade agreement is going to be put before <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for a final decision before Christmas and it is going to be put in place by Jan. 1,'' Trade Minister <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosbie </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Crosbie </PERSON> made the comment as he opened debate in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> on the third and final reading for the trade agreement's enabling legislation. Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won a second consecutive majority government in Nov. 21 elections, clearing the way for the trade agreement he signed with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in January. The party has been using its majority in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> to speed through the passage, but even the most drastic limits would require deputies to stay at work until about 1 a.m. Saturday, Christmas Day. Some evidently homesick members sang Christmas carols during debate that carried past midnight Wednesday. A delay of days, weeks or probably even several months would not hinder the agreement, which will phase out all remaining tariffs between the two countries over a 10-year period. But supporters of the agreement say it would be embarrassing for <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to have to ask the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to postpone the start of such a major undertaking. The approval in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGAN