<HEAD>Warsaw Extends Warm Welcome On Return Of Exiled Philosopher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Since philosopher <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> broke his 20-year exile to visit his homeland, he has been toasted by the opposition and ignored by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to which he once belonged. Hundreds of colleagues, friends and students too young to have heard the young <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> openly criticize Polish authorities have been filling auditoriums for the so-called `` Kolakowski Festival'' that began Monday. The lectures are the first in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> by the 61-year-old <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> since he was expelled from <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1968. <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON>'s works are published in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> only by the underground press. Based at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> has become one of the world's leading philosophers, winning fame for his three-volume `` History of Marxist Thought,'' which focuses on what the author calls discrepancies between dogma and practice in communist countries. `` The lectures have become a ` Kolakowski Festival' and an important one for us,'' said <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Turowicz </PERSON>, editor of the influential <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> weekly <ORGANIZATION> Tygodnik </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Powszechny </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. About 500 students, academics and leading members of the Polish opposition squeezed together on the dark wooden benches of the main auditorium at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Monday to hear <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON>'s first lecture. They gave <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> a two-minute standing ovation when he stood up to speak. <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> told the audience that when he left <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1968, three secret police cars accompanied him to the airport, while on this trip they have n't paid him any attention. On Wednesday, at an evening sponsored by the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> branch of the Club of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligentsia </ORGANIZATION> in the basement of a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> church, <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> easily answered questions on the existence of devils and mystics and the link between philosophy and religion. But when a question about the future of the banned trade union movement Solidarity was raised, <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> hesitated. `` I have no recipe. Nothing is guaranteed,'' he said. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> this year admitted wrongdoing in its purge of intellectuals and Jews in 1968 and made clear that the flood of scholars who left the country then were welcome to return. The granting of a visa to <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON>, visiting as a guest of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philosophical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, is the most dramatic acceptance to date of that invitation. <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> is expected to stay in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> about three weeks. <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> began his academic career as a party member in the early 1950s but quickly clashed with orthodox communist ideologues. In 1956, during a political thaw after <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s death known as the Polish October, <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> and a small group of communist intellectuals started Straight Talk, a lively journal of critical Marxist theory. The young philosopher urged the party to strive for `` integral democracy.'' For that view, the party leadership branded <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> a `` revisionist'' and Straight Talk survived only a year before authorities banned it. A 1966 university lecture on the Polish October, in which <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> accused authorities of breaking promises to the Polish people, cost the professor his party card. The final blow to <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON>'s academic career came when the Minister of Education revoked his chair after the philosopher defended students who had participated in March 1968 unrest. <PERSON> Kolakowski </PERSON> soon left <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and joined other Soviet bloc philosophers bloc forced into exile for their views, including <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukacs </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, deported to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> in 1956, and <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, who lost his chair at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leipzig </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1957. He taught at universities in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and finally settled at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
