<HEAD>SRP Manager Says Plant Could Be Started Immediately If Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION>'s reactors, which have been shut down by safety concerns, could be restarted immediately if the nation's defense demanded more nuclear weapons material, the complex's manager said. But plant manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> declined to say when he thought the plant in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> nearly 20 miles southeast of here would be restarted. `` I think that remains to be defined,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said in interviews published today in The <ORGANIZATION> Augusta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Augusta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. `` There has been speculation that it would be six months or 12 months. I really think until the ... criteria are well defined ... it's sheer speculation to pick a date. `` I certainly think they -LRB- the reactors -RRB- can be restarted safely. I think if the nation judged there was a need for the materials ... they could be restarted today.'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> was interviewed Thursday, on the same day <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> announced that ultrasonic testing would be used to check for possible cracks in reactor vessels. That could delay <ORGANIZATION> SRP </ORGANIZATION>'s restart until next summer. All three <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> reactors have been shut down since summer for safety upgrades and maintenance. The shutdown is one of a number of problems plaguing the nation's nuclear weapons production system, including plants in <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and Rocky Flats, <PERSON> Colo </PERSON>. Some have expressed concern the shutdown at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> could harm the nation's defense because the complex is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s only producer of tritium, an isotope of hydrogen which is a critical element in hydrogen bombs and which deteriorates at the rate of 5.5 percent a year. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> contended that the plant is safe to operate now, and said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> wants to increase the complex's `` margin of safety. The reactors have `` run safely for 35 years meeting the nation's needs,'' said <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, whose employer, <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>, runs the plant for DOE. `` They've run without a nuclear incident that was an injury to anybody either on or off the plant, and they've been continuously upgraded over that time.'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said politics have played a role in the debate over the plant's safety. Plant officials were criticized in congressional hearings earlier this year for not adequately reporting past safety problems. `` Certainly, if you go back in time from 1950 to this year, we have not only provided DOE with notification of what we considered significant events ... but also a wrapup of what it meant,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> countered. `` But with all the current attention, there is an increasing emphasis from the DOE to know things sooner and at a greater level of detail. And so we're working to develop a system and have that available to them. `` Some of it's clearly congressional pressure.'' <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> is wrapping up its involvement with the plant, which dates back to the plant's construction in the 1950s. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to take over operations of the facility April 1.
