 A police counterinsurgency unit active in the war against pro-independence guerrillas will be disbanded as a goodwill gesture following the agreement to end South African rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, a police official said today. The unit, with a reputation for tough and sometimes controversial tactics, is known as <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> Afrikaans </LOCATION> word for `` crowbar.'' Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand said the unit would be phased out gradually starting April 1, the beginning of a seven-month transition process leading to elections for a Naimibian national assembly. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> members have been involved in numerous court cases over the years related to allegations of brutality against black civilians in the northern war zone. Authorities have declined to disclose the number of men serving in the multiracial unit, but Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said Thursday that overall police strength in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> would be reduced from 8,300 to 7,000. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> was speaking at a news conference after joining Angolan and Cuban officials in signing agreements at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to bring about independence in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and remove <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops from neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> played a principal role in countering incursions by Angola-based insurgents of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which began a bush war against <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African rule in 1966 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored to win the Nov. 1 elect