<HEAD>Nobel Prize Winner For Medicine, Nikolaas Tinbergen, Dead At 81</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to ADD that Tinbergen died Wednesday.
Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Born in...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nikolaas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON>, a Dutch-born British zoologist who won the Nobel Prize for Medicine in 1973, has died of an apparent stroke, his widow said today. He was 81. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutten </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that her husband of 56 years had `` quite reasonably recovered'' from a first stroke in 1983. He died Wednesday shortly after apparently suffering another stroke at his <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> home. Born in The Hague in 1907, <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON> studied at universities in <LOCATION> Leiden </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He gained prominence in the late 1930s as one of the founders of ethology, the branch of biology that studies animal behavior. During World War II, he was detained by the occupying German forces at a detention camp in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. After a pre-war spell with <PERSON> Konrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenz </PERSON>, the noted German zoologist, he was appointed professor of experimental zoology at <ORGANIZATION> Leiden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1947. Two years later, he became an ethology lecturer at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where he wrote `` The Study of Instinct,'' considered the first handbook on ethology ever published. He was a professor in animal behavior at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> from 1966 to 1974, and a professor emeritus there until his death. <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON>, who became a British citizen in 1955, was a prolific writer and an accomplished maker of nature films. He shared the 1973 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine with <PERSON> Lorenz </PERSON> and Austrian zoologist <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON> for their `` discoveries in the field of the organization and occurrence of individual and social behavioral patterns'' in the animal world. The 1973 prize was a new departure for the Nobel committee, acknowledging for the first time major advances in man's understanding of sociobiology, especially in the behavioral science known as ethology `` At one stroke, they -LRB- the three laureates -RRB- explained some of the most remarkable examples of the fine control of elaborate patterns of behavior by external stimuli known to science, sometimes learned, sometimes not, while leaving in no doubt the crucial importance of genetic differences in understanding the development of behavior,'' the British magazine Science said of their award. <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON>'s elder brother, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON>, won the first-ever Nobel Prize for Economics in 1969. <PERSON> Tinbergen </PERSON> is survived by his widow, two sons and three daughters.
