<HEAD>Bush Office Confirms Son And Grandson Of President-Elect To Go To
Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s son and grandson will travel to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> on Christmas Day to help distribute <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> aid to earthquake victims, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s office confirmed today. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> told the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` will participate in a ceremony of transferring to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> relief aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 35, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> real estate developer, and his son, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, 12, will spend about six hours in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital, on Christmas Day, said the transition office. They leave <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Saturday, arriving in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on <PERSON> Christman </PERSON> morning. The Bushes are traveling to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> as volunteers for <ORGANIZATION> Americares </ORGANIZATION>, a relief agency that has chartered a DC-8 cargo plane to transport supplies to the region. The aid will include medicine, medical equipment and toys from the Americares charity for children who survived the Dec. 7 quake, which killed at least 55,000 people, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, an Americares spokesman, said the Bushes are among three people on the flight. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> said the Bushes will only stay a few hours because of time restrictions imposed by the Soviets. `` They are not allowing people to stay much longer than that because of congestion at the airport,'' he said. The plane will return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after a brief layover in <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> said.
