<HEAD>Pressure-Activated Bomb Found During Palestinian Arrests In October</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with report of security lapse at airport. No
pickup.
^With PM-Crash, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German official said today that police discovered an air pressure-activated bomb during the October arrests of suspected radical Palestinians, but he emphasized it was too soon to say whether there was any connection to the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet. `` It's pure speculation,'' said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Prechtel </PERSON>, spokesman for the chief federal prosecutor's office. The bomb is set off by a drop in air pressure, such as those occurring in the luggage compartment of an airplane, he said. New York-bound <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and landed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where passengers changed from a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 to the ill-fated <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747. Wednesday's crash in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, which killed 258 people on board and at least 22 people on the ground, apparently occurred after the plane broke up for an unknown reason at an altitude of 31,000 feet. The <ORGANIZATION> Neue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presse </ORGANIZATION> newspaper of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> reported today on alleged lapses in security checks at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport. The newspaper quoted an unidentified expert as saying it's `` problem-free to smuggle a bomb on board.'' `` If the explosives and detonator are taken on board separately, it's all child's play,'' the newspaper quoted the expert as saying. The paper quoted an unidentified baggage handler as saying that not every bag is subjected to an X-ray scan, and that only random samplings are made. <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwalm </PERSON>, the spokesman for the airport, declined comment on the report, noting that security is handled by <PERSON> Hesse </PERSON> state officials. The Associated Press called the office of security chief <PERSON> Horst </PERSON> <PERSON> Harnstein </PERSON>, and was told he was not available to talk. But on Thursday, <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Neusel </PERSON>, the No. 2 official in the federal <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, strongly defended security at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport. <PERSON> Arno </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON>, a spokesman for the federal police office in <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that West German investigators were checking details of the crash and were in contact with investigators in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Since the crash, there have been growing indications the flight was sabotaged. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the Independent newspaper today quoted a security source as saying investigators were taking `` very seriously'' a pro-Iranian group's letter that it was responsible for the crash. However, <PERSON> Prechtel </PERSON> brought up the issue of 13 Palestinians rounded up in a series of raids in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in October. Three were later arrested, while the others were set free but remain under investigation. <PERSON> Prechtel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the arrested suspects belonged to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command. `` They have said they planned attacks against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests,'' <PERSON> Prechtel </PERSON> said of the suspected Popular Front members. The suspects allegedly set up a terrorist cell of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, authorities say. The Syrian-controlled faction is opposed to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZ