<HEAD>Court Upholds Convictions of Rebellious Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court convicted seven retired air force officers for attempting to take over an airport following an army insurrection in January. The three-member court rejected the officers' arguments that they tried to seize <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <LOCATION> Newberry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to prevent a civil war. One officer testified that they wanted to stop an air force attack on rebellious army units at <LOCATION> Monte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caseros </LOCATION>, 310 miles northeast of the capital. The army units later surrendered. Thursday's decision by the appeals court came after the nation's highest military tribunal convicted the seven of mutiny and sentenced them The appeals court convicted the men on the more serious charge of aggravated rebellion. Most received stiffer sentences. Under Argentine law, the appeals court can rule on any charges or assign its own penalties independent of lower or military court rulings. Retired Col. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrella </PERSON>'s sentence of 12 years was upheld, while the sentences of Lt. Cols. <PERSON> Horacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricciardelli </PERSON>, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Puy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavella </PERSON> were increased to 11 years each. Under the military tribunal, <PERSON> Puy </PERSON> had received an eight-year sentence, and <LOCATION> Lavella </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ricciardelli </PERSON> seven years each. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, Maj. <PERSON> Higinio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribles </PERSON> and Capt. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> all received sentences of six years, eight months; as did <PERSON> Godofredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Buschiazzo </PERSON>, an enlisted man in the navy. <PERSON> Ribles </PERSON> had originally received a seven-year sentence, and <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> received five years each. <PERSON> Buschiazzo </PERSON>'s term was increased from one to five years. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Magni </PERSON>, who had argued he did not participate in the takeover, was acquitted. He had received a three-year sentence from the military tribunal. The convicted servicemen will spend their terms in military custody. On Jan. 18, about 20 rebels seized the control tower, forcing the cancellation of some flights and the detour of others to <ORGANIZATION> Ezeiza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, the largest in this city of 10 million. Rebels surrendered peacefully after four hours. <PERSON> Estrella </PERSON> told the court that he and the others acted to prevent the air force attack against the rebels in <LOCATION> Monte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caseros </LOCATION>. `` On Jan. 18, the country was heading towards a civil war and something had to be done to prevent the repression the air force was ready to launch on the rebels,'' <PERSON> Estrella </PERSON> said. The army insurrection was led by Lt. Col. <PERSON> Aldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rico </PERSON>, now cashiered and imprisoned at an army garrison along with about 50 of his followers. None have been brought to trial. <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> also led an uprising in April 1987 to protest the trial of officers for human rights abuses stemming from the repression of subversion under the 1976-83 military dictatorship. That same concern prompted a third uprising against the civilian government of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> earlier this month.
