<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christmas Eve will be `` Silent Night'' for almost 800 pirate radio stations slated to shut down indefinitely as part of a government plan to restructure broadcasting. The center-right Social Democrat government has ordered the Saturday closure while it evaluates offers from stations for control of 430 frequencies that will be available for local broadcast in 1989. `` Final offers have to be submitted by Jan. 3. But the problem is -LRB- the government -RRB- has n't said how long stations will be closed for,'' said <PERSON> Emidio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, director of TSF, a major commercial station that will close one day before the deadline to allow its employees to spend Christmas with their families. <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> said between 2,000 and 3,000 people could lose their jobs because of the closure. Pirate stations began broadcasting on the FM band in 1977 but, with names like <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unforeseen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chaos </ORGANIZATION>, most were amateur. Successive governments tolerated the pirates, and the unregulated stations boomed. TSF, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s most popular station among listeners in the 25-45 age group, boasted a closing program Friday with live interviews with President <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, marathon star <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Mota </PERSON> and leading politicians. The station, set up in February this year with a capital of $ 690,000, has no plans to lay off its 75-strong staff, said TSF journalist <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Marinho </PERSON>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> is committed long-term to liberalizing the state national broadcasting monopoly, but the government plans to hand over only one frequency to a national commercial network at a future date. The government has b