<HEAD>Lawmakers Approve AIDS Prevention Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators gave final approval Friday to a law intended to track and prevent the spread of AIDS. The law, to take effect next year, would require doctors to report to local governors the name, age and sex of any AIDS patient and how the victim contracted the disease, said an official at the research office of the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, a government agency. The law also authorize governors to fine anyone refusing to be tested for AIDS up to $ 800, and to punish doctors who disclose information about AIDS patients to anyone but the governor's office, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the law provides for banning entry to any foreigner believed likely to engage in activities that could spread acquired immune deficience syndrome, although AIDS tests are not mandatory for foreigners. Most opposition members voted against the bill, saying it would lead to people avoiding seeing their doctors. The government says 50 people have died of AIDS in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> as of Aug. 31, with 90 confirmed AIDS patients and 1,048 known carriers of the virus.
