<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commandos with explosive charges attacked the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and military headquarters in the capital today, military sources said. No casualties were immediately reported. It was the first time the installation, which houses the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and the joint chiefs of staff, was attacked during <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s nine-year guerrilla war. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, gave no other details. Radio reports indicated that two car bombs detonated near the walled compound in the southwest part of the city, but the reports could not be immediately confirmed. No one claimed responsibility, but the attackers were presumed to be members of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a left-wing insurgency trying to overthrow the government. In the last year, it has attacked installations in the capital with car bombs and catapult-launched homemade bombs. Earlier in the day, unidentified terrorists killed a night watchman and set off three bombs, destroying the interior of the biology lab building at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, an official at the institution said. The official told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that unidentified individuals cut through a metal fence before dawn to enter the campus in the capital's northwestern sector. The official, who commented on condition of anonymity, identified the slain watchman as <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguirre </PERSON>. No one claimed responsibility for the attack at the university, with 35,000 students the biggest in the country, and police said they had no clues on the identity of the attackers. The university has been the scene of demonstrations recently by leftist student unions demanding $ 1.2 million in additional appropriations to pay back salaries for December owed to teachers and workers. Students were also protesting the assassination last week of a woman director of a law faculty extension in the western city of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>. The interior of the building, including furniture, files, windows, ceilings and laboratory equipment, was virtually demolished by the blasts. Also today, five provincial town mayors resigned, bringing to 12 the number of mayors who quit during the past three months after receiving death threats from leftist guerrillas fighting for power. The guerrillas have assassinated nine mayors in 1988. They say the officials were `` executed'' for their part in implementing what the rebels call `` the U.S.-imposed counterinsurgency plan.''
