<HEAD>Plane's Delayed Departure May Be Helpful Factor In Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after pvs 3rd graf bgng ``Witnesses saw ...''
to update with what investigators heard on flight recordings;
INSERTS 2 grafs after pvs 7th graf bgng ``U.S. officials...'' to
include call to AP's London office on Thursday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If a terrorist bomb brought down <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103, a 25-minute delay of the jet's departure from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> may provide investigators with their biggest advantage. It kept the wreckage on land, instead of falling into the ocean. The cause of Wednesday's crash that killed all 258 people on board and more than 20 on the ground has yet to be determined, but there were signs today pointing to an explosion. Witnesses saw a flash of light high in the sky as the jet plummeted toward the ground; there was no communication from the cockpit as would have been expected if the pilots encountered flight control problems, and the wreckage was strewn over miles of Scottish countryside with the cockpit section found more than three miles from other large parts of the aircraft. From <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, officials investigating the crash said today that the cockpit recording of the flight's last minutes ended abruptly after a faint noise. They also said conversations among the crew gave no clues about what caused the plane to crash. `` There is nothing in the conversations -LRB- of the flight crew -RRB- to indicate anything was wrong,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McKie </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION>. The cockpit recording and flight data tapes from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 were being analyzed by the department's Air Accident Investigation Branch. `` There is a faint noise at the end which needs a bit more analysis. There is no indication what that noise is,'' said <PERSON> McKie </PERSON>. But none of that is conclusive evidence that a bomb detonated aboard the jetliner. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said today that a public warning about the flight after an anonymous telephone call to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> would `` literally have closed down air traffic in the world.'' The president said he believes `` all precautions'' were taken in the warning which went to the airline and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, speaking in the rain outside the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as he departed for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> where he will spend the holidays, offered condolences to the families of the victims, calling for Christmas prayers for their loss. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the caller to the embassy in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> on Dec. 5 said that a bomb would be planted aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> within two weeks. Flight 103 began in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> on a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, then changed planes to a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. But there has been no evidence that the telephone tip was related to the crash of Flight 103. In addition, an anonymous caller to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Thursday claimed a pro-Iranian group called Guardians of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolution </ORGANIZATION> planted a bomb on the plane. The caller said the motive was revenge for the July downing of an Iranian jetliner in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has denied involvement in the crash. The wreckage of Flight 103 is expected to provide more definitive clues, and while it is strewn over miles of countryside, at least it is not hundreds of feet under wintry seas, some aviation experts noted. In other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> developments related to the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash: _ White House officials defended the process by which the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> warned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies _ but not the general public _ that a bomb threat had been made against <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> They said the government would review whether public notification should be considered in future such cases. _ President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that if there were `` hard evidence'' that a specific flight was threatened or that the threat could not be averted, the public should be warned Nevertheless, he said most such threats `` never materialize.'' _ <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> there have been `` a number of calls'' from individuals _ some claiming to speak for various terrorist groups _ taking responsibility for the crash Sessions provided no specifics. Flight 103 had been airborne 54 minutes when it disappeared from radar screens while cruising at 31,000 feet over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. It was about to head westbound over the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> when tragedy struck. Another half hour and the plane would have been well over water. `` You would have had another <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> situation,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, an aviation safety consultant and former longtime investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. To many investigators, the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> tragedy appears to resemble the l985 crash of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 off the Irish coast. That jumbo jet also plummeted from the sky from 31,000 feet without a hint of trouble from the pilots. But the wreckage landed in the ocean and salvage crews struggled for four months to gather pieces, including the `` black box'' recorders, that would provide clues. An analysis of the final split second of the voice recorder was key to Indian officials concluding that a bomb had exploded aboard the aircraft. The authorities probing the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash clearly will have more to work with. They already have found the critical `` black box'' recorders _ one that monitors cockpit conversation and noises and another that records aircraft performance. Investigators will pay close attention to how parts of the aircraft are bent, tangled and singed and whether there are signs of residue from an explosion. They also will search for fragments that might have been used as a detonator and closely examine luggage and parts of luggage for residue from an explosive. The `` black box'' recorders are likely to provide, as they do in most aviation crashes, the most critical evidence, say aviation experts. The tape from the cockpit recorder may be as important for what it does n't say as for what it does, say veteran investigators. Is there a fragmented sound of an explosion? Are there any exchanges between pilots about control problems? Did the tape suddenly stop with no evidence of an emergency or structural concern? If all seems normal right to the end, it will be strong evidence that a powerful explosion might have knocked out communications, electricity and perhaps even literally severed the cockpit from the rest of the aircraft, says <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. `` If you lost all communications, lost all electrical power on and airplane, the pilots now are nothing more than passengers.'' It would not take a large amount of explosives to do the job, suggested a number of experts. `` If a bomb severs some major or important electrical wiring, or hydraulic lines or cables, you could lose your ability to control the airplane,'' noted <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. While aviation experts were reluctant to provide details that could be used as a primer for terrorism, it is generally known that if an explosive device _ even a small one _ can be placed in certain areas of the baggage compartment of a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, it could wipe out critical computer, electrical and communications systems as well as possibly incapacitate the flight crew. Some safety experts say such a scenario explains the sudden loss of communications while the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet was at cruise altitude and its rapid fall and breakup while still in the sky. They point out that commercial jetliners have over the years been kept aloft for some time even when encountering major structural problems short of an explosion. In l985, the pilots of a <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 struggled to keep their plane flying for about 32 minutes after a failure in the rear cabin bulkhead caused rapid depressurization. The jet finally crashed into a mountain, killing 520 people aboard.
