<HEAD>Army Grounds Chinooks for Transmission Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it has grounded its 234 CH-47D medium-lift Chinook helicopters to allow inspection of possibly faulty transmissions. Ten Chinooks have been involved in accidents since 1985, and 16 soldiers were killed in incidents involving the helicopter this year, although there is no indication that faulty transmissions were the cause, said <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Paige </PERSON> <PERSON> Eversole </PERSON>. The Army grounded the copter fleet in what it called a `` precautionary action'' after the manufacturer, the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, discovered that `` certain transmissions may have been improperly assembled,'' the announcement said. In the most recent Chinook accident, five servicemen were killed in a crash in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> on Dec. 8. Last Feb. 25, 11 soldiers were killed in a Chinook crash near <LOCATION> Chico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Army officials are still investigating the Dec. 8 incident, but there is `` no suspicion'' that it was linked to the possible transmission problem, Ms. <PERSON> Eversole </PERSON> said. `` Right now we are not speculating at all on the cause of that accident. We do n't know whether there is a relationship between that accident and this problem. The Army is very quick to ground the fleet ... for preventive care,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> is sending inspection teams to look at the retainer bolt assembly, which provides for the proper alignment of internal gearing and bearings within the main transmission, the spokeswoman said. The inspections will require 30 days, according to the announcement. The first Chinook CH-47D entered Army service in 1979, replacing older CH-47 models. The Army is gradually replacing the remaining 146 older Chinooks with the `` D'' model, which has more powerful engines and transmissions, fiberglass rotor blades, and advanced flight control systems, the announcement said. The Chinook can carry a payload of 16,000 pounds or ferry 33 soldiers. The helicopter that crashed in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> was on a routine mission connected with maneuvers the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has been conducting in that Central American country since 1982. In the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> crash, `` the retainer bolt assembly was not identified as a possible cause,'' Ms. <PERSON> Eversole </PERSON> said. Despite the recent crashes involving the Chinook, the fiscal year thaty ended Sept. 30 `` was the safest year on record, with 1.8 accidents per 100,000 hours of flying time for all Army aviation,'' she said.
