<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     12-23 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Key Laws on Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The parliament on Friday approved bills to encourge private ownership and foreign investment in an attempt to reverse four decades of state economic control. The Communist government pushed the two pieces of legislation, which become law Jan. 1, to radically alter the structure of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s socialist economy. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s 460-member Sejm, or parliament, unanimously approved the new Law on Economic Activity, which eliminates limits on the size of businesses that can be privately owned. There were two abstentions. The foreign investment bill drew two `` no'' votes and six abstentions, the official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Private business now accounts for about 6 percent of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s non-farm economy, but Industry Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilczek </PERSON> _ calling the bills' passage a `` historic breakthrough'' _ has said he hopes thousands of new businesses will open next year The new law on economic activity removes past discrimination against private ownership, treating state-owned, cooperative and private businesses the same for legal purposes. Private businesses previously were limited in size to 50 employees and needed permission from administrative officials to operate. Businesses could be turned down if a local official deemed them unneeded or said they interfered with an existing state or cooperative monopoly. But the new law removes any ceiling on the size of the work force and allows individuals, cooperatives, partnerships and limited liability companies to start and operate businesses as long as they comply with safety, environmental and fire protection laws. However, 11 areas of activity _ such as weapons manufacture, production and sales of pharmaceuticals and alcohol or operation of sea and air transport _ will require prior government licenses because they involve public safety. Firms are freed from the previous obligation to associate with industrial or professional groups. Despite the government's high hopes for the legislation, there were some doubts. `` To ... be able to invest in something, one has to have something to invest,'' said an article Sunday in the weekly magazine <ORGANIZATION> Wprost </ORGANIZATION>. `` The majority of Polish families spend their earnings on current consumption and can not afford'' to start businesses. Only `` richer citizens have now gained an opportunity to show what they can do,'' the article concludes. The law on foreign investment combines and replaces two old laws, one for investment by foreigners of Polish descent and one for everyone else. In both cases the rules are now easier. A foreign investor must put up at least 20 percent of the start-up cost of any business or joint venture, and the business will be subject to a 40 percent income tax _ lower if the company produces for export. Unlike previous laws, there are no requirements that majority control and local management be Polish. Companies will have access to currency auctions where they can convert profits earned in zlotys to hard currency at market rates. They also will be allowed to sell to Poles in hard currency. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> passed a foreign-investment bill in 1986 but businesses considered its terms so unattractive that only about a dozen companies took advantage of it. Authorities hope that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s low wage scale and skilled work force will attract manufacturing and service facilities to serve other European countries. The deputy prime minister, <PERSON> Ireneusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sekula </PERSON>, presented the legislation to parliament Thursday, saying the laws would become the basis `` for freedom, equality and competition in the economy.'' Departing from orthodox communist assumptions of an equal share in the wealth for all citizens, he defined the state's duty only as creating `` equal opportunity.'' `` Further possibilities should depend on -LRB- people's -RRB- individual achievements,'' he said. `` This is the only way one should understand justice.'' Parliamentarian <PERSON> Lucien </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepien </PERSON> said that in the context of decades of `` Stalinist governing'' the new laws might seem `` revolutionary.'' But in reality, he said, `` they are just an attempt to get back to normal.''
</TEXT>
