<TEXT>
 Nearly a year after a polygamist clan began a fatal confrontation with the law, a jury's verdict has ended another chapter in a saga begun 15 years ago on the family's northern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> homestead The homicide convictions of three young clan members, said one prosecutor, puts to rest the `` legend of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>,'' whose 1979 death at the hands of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> lawmen triggered the bombing of a Mormon chapel last January and the clan's 13-day armed standoff at their Marion farm. An eight-member 3rd District Court jury in <LOCATION> Coalville </LOCATION> on Thursday convicted clan patriarch <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 27, and Singer's son, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, 22, of manslaughter in the death of state Corrections Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, gunned down during a botched arrest that ended the siege. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 21, was convicted of negligent homicide. Singer admitted firing the fatal shot and <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> said he also shot his rifle, but <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, who was seriously wounded by an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> sharpshooter, insisted he never fired. `` It's over,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwendiman </PERSON>, who also prosecuted the trio and Singer's widow, <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON>, in federal court last spring. `` They just simply ca n't bring <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> out to justify what they have done and want to do,'' he said. `` It's over, and if this year has n't proved that in <LOCATION> spades </LOCATION>, nothing will.'' It was 1973 when <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, a German immigrant and excommunicated Mormon who embraced polygamy and other Mor