<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> came home Friday after five days in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and said his visit restored the friendly Indian-Chinese relations of the early 1950s. Also Friday, about 100 Tibetan students outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> set fire to a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> flag and denounced <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s recognition of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> as part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Police with bamboo canes watched the rally but did generally not interfere. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> told a news conference at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s international airport, `` I believe this visit will be a new beginning for both countries.'' A border dispute has strained relations between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the world's two most populous countries, for nearly three decades. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has more than 1 billion people, and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has about 800 million. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was the first by an Indian prime minister since his grandfather, <PERSON> Jawaharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, visited <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1954. The two countries issued a communique in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> earlier Friday, agreeing to set up a joint working group to take up the territorial dispute, which led to war in 1962. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said the group would set a time frame in which to resolve the issue. The communique also said Chinese Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> has accepted an invitation to visit <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, but no date was set. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> claims 36,000 square miles of mountainous frontier that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> says is part of its Arunachal Pradesh state. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also says <LOCATION> China <