<HEAD>U.S. Forces Close Firing Range After Complaints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said Friday they were halting all live firing training at an <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> range where neighbors complained that bullets strayed into nearby residential areas. The announcement by <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Forces <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> did not refer directly to complaints that followed exercises Oct. 15 at a Camp Hansen firing range on the southern Japanese island. But it said `` senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have expressed deep regret over recent incidents and have emphasized the respect and appreciation American military forces feel for the people of <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> and their culture.'' After local officials said nine bullets were reported found in a village opposite the range's target area. No one was reported injured, but two Foreign Ministry officials went to <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> last month to talk with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> generals and inspect firing ranges. The announcement also said that demonstration flights by F-15 jet fighters at <LOCATION> Kadena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, also on <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>, were suspended indefinitely. It gave no reason. Maj. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothfork </PERSON>, spokeman for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said safety regulations for other firing ranges had been reviewed, permanent safety officers would be present for all live firing training, the direction of firing would be restricted, and safety education would be increased. Weeks after the firing range complaints, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ship fired practice shells that landed about 330 yards from a <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> vessel near the entrance to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> immediately expressed regret, and relieved the ship's skipper of command. But the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> lodged a protest with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, and Japanese newspaper editorials published blistering editorials. About 64,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops are in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> under a security treaty. About 35,000 of them are stationed in <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>, an island of 1.2 million people.
