<HEAD>Cockpit Recording Has `Faint Noise' at Point of Disaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 38th graf pvs, _An Air India ... UPDATING with nothing
found. Picks up 39th graf, _An unattended ... Minor editing
throughout to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XDUM1,LON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cockpit recording of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103's final minutes ended with a brief, mysterious `` faint noise'' and gave no sign that the pilots knew their <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 was doomed, investigators said Friday. Conversations captured by the `` black box'' that records all cockpit activity was normal up to the `` faint noise at the end which needs a bit more analysis,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McKie </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> of the department's Air Accident Investigation Branch, who is heading a team of 40 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British investigators at the crash site, said: `` We have no evidence whatsoever yet of sabotage.'' The plane, flying from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, broke up at 31,000 feet Wednesday night, killing all 258 people aboard and bombarding the Scottish countryside with flaming wreckage over a 10-mile radius. Flowers arrived at the scene Friday. A passenger who had left the flight at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> sent a bouquet to a child flying on to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, with the message: `` To the little girl in the red dress who lies here, who made my flight from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> such fun. You did n't deserve this.'' Suspicions of sabotage were prompted by the inexplicable sudden breakup of the plane, a claim of responsibility and disclosures that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government had been warned of a plot to bomb a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight between <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in December. Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> with a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, and switched to a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Soldiers hacked open the nose section, lying on its side in a field, and removed the bodies of crew members on stretchers and under tarpaulins. From 20 to 30 relatives of victims arrived in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, the Scottish village that bore the brunt of the crash, and 155 bodies were placed in makeshift morgues in the town hall and ice rink. The relatives included at least seven Americans. They were advised against visiting the wreckage, said Superintendent <PERSON> Angus </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a police spokesman in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. More than 600 police and military personnel spent Friday scouring the countryside for bodies and wreckage, but only one more body was found. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said whether it was of a passenger or ground victim was not known. Fourteen adults and three children were missing in the <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> area and there was no word on the occupants of three cars hit by wreckage and gutted on a nearby highway, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. He said it had been learned the driver of a fourth car was treated for injuries Wednesday night and released, and the driver of a fifth car was a villager and counted among the 17 residents listed as missing. Arc lights and heavy lifting equipment were brought in to speed the search. Searchers moved shoulder to shoulder across fields and marshes, trying to collect every scrap of evidence. A faint smell of aviation fuel lingered. During the night, a party of Jewish youths clambered over the rubble, apparently searching for holy items like prayer books that might have been with Jewish passengers and require ritual burial. All indications were that the plane broke up in seconds, and that the cockpit never knew of the imminent catastrophe. `` There were no abnormal noises on the -LRB- cockpit recorder's -RRB- tape until the signals ended abruptly with the aircraft cruising at 31,000 feet,'' said <PERSON> McKie </PERSON>. There was `` nothing in the conversations to indicate anything was wrong,'' he said, adding that no conclusions could be drawn yet from the noise at the end of the tape. On Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said the plane's radar blip on the Scottish ground control screens `` split into several returns'' before vanishing <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> told a news conference the wreckage was `` spread over a very, very long wreckage trail,'' but added this did not indicate sabotage. The spread was normal, given the plane's altitude and the 115-knot winds at 31,000 feet. People have found papers, clothing and mail up to 70 miles from <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. Three teen-age boys found a bundle of $ 500,000 in travelers' checks in the hills near their home six miles from <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, police said Friday. `` To try and prejudge this case would be totally wrong. There are obviously a number of potential causes for an in-flight breakup. We are looking for evidence to try and point us in the right direction. To suggest that it would be one or the other at this stage would be wrong,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> said. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sent a message to the 2,500 people of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> saying: `` Our hearts go out to you on this tragic occasion which marred what should have been a season of joy.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Park </PERSON> of the local district council wrote back: `` Our small community has suffered much but our sadness is even greater when we think of the loss of so many people from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Our thoughts are with their friends and relatives wherever they may be.'' A newspaper Friday quoted a security source as saying investigators were taking `` very seriously'' a group's claim of responsibility. The Independent quoted the source as saying the group is thought to have sought revenge for the July 3 downing of an Iranian jetliner by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. An anonymous caller to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> claimed Thursday the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution was responsible for the crash. A political dispute arose over the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s disclosure that it knew of a bomb threat two weeks before the crash but did not pass it on to <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> or the public <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials told British officials that an anonymous caller to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, said Dec. 5 that a bomb would be planted aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> within two weeks. Transport Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Portillo </PERSON> said it was `` confidential, classified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence information and we did n't have the right to divulge it.'' He said the warning prompted an assessment of <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> security for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flights. The security was judged to be appropriate. Also on Friday: _ An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet bound for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with 250 people aboard returned to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>