<HEAD>School Unfairly Punished Review Editors, Lawyer Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 7th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVERHILL, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION>'s board of trustees said Friday that he did not influence a disciplinary panel that suspended two student journalists although he was unhappy with their publication. At a court hearing to determine whether the two stdents should be reinstated, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> McCulloch </PERSON> testified his initial reaction to the off-campus, conservative <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> was favorable. `` I thought it was extremely important to have a conservative viewpoint demonstrated and published on campus,'' <PERSON> McCulloch </PERSON> said in <ORGANIZATION> Grafton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` But I became really disenchanted when the Review began to go away from a focus on the issues and began to focus on personalities.'' <PERSON> McCulloch </PERSON> said, however, that he did not try to influence the campuswide disciplinary board that suspended former Review editors <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> for 18 months in March. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON>, 22, of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> want Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohl </PERSON> to let them return to school before their suspensions expire in September. <PERSON> Mohl </PERSON> is expected to rule before classes resume Jan. 3. They and two other students were accused of harassing music professor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> during a classroom confrontation after a Review article disparaged <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>'s course. Cole, who is black, once was described by the Review as looking `` like a used Brillo pad.'' He testified this week that he considered the latest Review criticisms racially motivated, a charge denied by <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>. The hearing ended Friday after the judge prevented the school's lawyer from trying to show that the former editors sought a heavy penalty in order to generate more publicity for their case <PERSON> Mohl </PERSON> ruled as irrelevant an attempt by <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON> to show that <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sutter </PERSON> intentionally sought the 18-month suspension. <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON> argued it was `` extremely relevant'' because it was `` important to get a maximum suspension and therefore to get maximum press exposure.'' The students' lawyer, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, disputed <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON>'s claim, calling it `` one of the most extraordinary things I've ever heard.'' When the hearing began Monday, <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> said the suspensions had national implications because of their chilling effect on college journalists nationwide. But <PERSON> Mohl </PERSON> also called that argument irrelevant. The two students argue that <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> discriminates against conservatives, disciplining them for infractions more harshly than liberal students, a charge college officials deny. Two lawsuits, one in state and one in federal court, have been filed against the school based on this allegation.
