<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speculation that an explosion may have caused a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jet to crash in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to issue a call for increased security at airports worldwide, officials said Friday. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> told reporters that the security alert was sent to airlines, foreign governments and major airports both in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad on Thursday. He said it was prompted by a combination of factors, including the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash Wednesday, the heavy Christmas travel rush and `` what obviously can be considered a heightening of world tensions'' as it pertains to terrorist activities. The alert was not prompted by any single threat or piece of intelligence information, officials said. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>, in an interview with a small group of reporters, declined to discuss specifically the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> crash that killed all 258 people aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 jumbo jet and leaving at least 17 people missing on the ground. The plane apparently broke apart in the air, possibly because of a terrorist bomb. The crash came two weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> sent the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> a bulletin warning that <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> might be the subject of a terrorist bombing on its flights from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 that crashed was Flight 103, which had originated at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. Disclosure of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> bulletin in early December _ the 23rd such alert this year _ has prompted questions over whether such notices should be shared with the public. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said earlier Friday that a public warning based on an anonymous telephone call _ as was the case with the alert involving <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> _ would have been an overreaction. It `` would literally have closed down air traffic in the world,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in answer to a reporter's question. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> praised <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s response to the alert at the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport, saying the airline had imposed `` a very heightened level of security.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s precautions at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, from which Flight 103 departed 54 minutes before the crash, were still under review. At <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> briefed gate personnel about the possible threat, kept ground baggage handlers and caterers `` under constant surveillance'' and checked all luggage by X-ray instead of only at random. All passengers and their bags also were matched prior to boarding, he said. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said that while there is no hard evidence of sabotage in connection with Flight 103, he is concerned about the possibility that a bomb could be placed aboard the jetliner at two airports where security precautions are among the best in the world and where a heightened alert was in effect. `` If there was a door -LRB- of opportunity for terrorists -RRB- left open, we've got to find out what allowed that and close that door,'' he said.
