<HEAD>NBC Documentary Spotlights `Sarafina'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the recent wave of South African theatrical productions exposing the oppression of apartheid, the most popular is the surprisingly exuberant Broadway musical `` Sarafina!'' Television viewers who do n't expect to be in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> anytime soon can get a taste of the show and a look behind the scenes in an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> special Wednesday, `` ` Sarafina' ... Words of Freedom, Songs of Hope,'' a one-hour version of documentary maker <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON>'s feature-length film The film includes snippets of the incredibly infectious music composed by <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Masakela </PERSON> and the playwright, <PERSON> Mbongeni </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngema </PERSON>, and touching interviews with the talented cast of black South African teen-agers who tell wrenching tales of repression, beatings and deaths of loved ones, but also express hope for the future. `` I'd seen the play and had always wanted to do something to explain what apartheid did to people,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> senior executive producer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>. `` CBS did a good show last year -LRB- the documentary ` Children of Apartheid' -RRB-. But the way these kids talk about it and act through the play, they explain what happened to them in their own lives. They describe their hope, and after all that has happened to them, they really want to go back.'' The film is `` a departure for us, because there are hardly any <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> people, just the kids and the music,'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung </PERSON> appears briefly to explain to viewers what they are about to see. At one point, <PERSON> Ngema </PERSON> lectures his young charges about their mission in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` The South African Embassy has ambassadors here, and ambassadors are people who speak for them. The black people of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> do n't have an embassy here, so this is the embassy and you are the ambassadors.'' The kids have been immensely successful. The show opened at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in October 1987 and moved to the Cort Theater on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. It won rave reviews and has been selling out nightly. The show is a loose flow of sketches about the lives of students at <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Isaacson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, a school that prides itself on its political consciousness. <PERSON> Sarafina </PERSON> is a popular girl and one of the student leaders. Many of the musical numbers are joyous, even funny. But late in the play, <PERSON> Sarafina </PERSON>'s incarceration and torture by police _ unseen _ gives fire to the other students' commitment. When she returns unbowed, there is a climactic dance number in which the kids hurl themselves with deadly result at the military figures who double as the on-stage band. In an interview, cast member <PERSON> Dumisani </PERSON> <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON> describes the reality that inspired the scene. `` I have seen things happening in front of my face. I have seen my brothers dying, and I have seen my heroes dying. So how shall I sit down? I have to stand and fight. Then I'll be free.'' `` Theater in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> at the moment plays a very important role,'' says <PERSON> Ngema </PERSON>. `` We do n't read a lot in the newspaper about what is happening in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. And newspapers outside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> can not report everything they want to report. So theater at this point in time has become the only voice left.'' <PERSON> Ngema </PERSON> recruited the youngsters from black townships and lived with the entire cast together in one small house for three months. He got permission from their parents to take them 8,000 miles away to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by promising they would get a good education. He explains that most South African black children do n't attend school because the education they receive is poor and schools are subject to riots and police sweeps. Most Americans probably can not imagine how children raised under crushing oppression could attain Broadway fame and still long to return to their homeland, but the kids do. `` I will go back to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, because it's where I belong, too,'' says <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>. `` It's my home. I'll die in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. That's what I think.'' The climactic moment in the film comes when the children meet singer <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Makeba </PERSON>, a spiritual leader for them despite her 27 years in exile. They are so overwhelmed by seeing her in person, they cry and cling to her, then break into song. She is moved to tears. `` I may die in exile today, but I will die very happy knowing that you will continue to do all that I started doing,'' <PERSON> Makeba </PERSON> says, `` spreading the message through your music and your lovely voices to the world, telling them and showing them that we are a proud people, and that we are, in fact, a struggling people, and that we will win our independence, and we'll be free like all other people in the world.''
</TEXT>
