<HEAD>Civil Rights Movement Comes to the Screen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the summer of 1964, 1,000 young volunteers from mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> arrived in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to help register black voters. They were idealistic and committed, believing their enthusiasm and good intentions could make a difference. But it was a time when <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s `` dream'' had not yet stemmed the hate and violence of segregation: During that season of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Summer Project there were 1,000 arrests, 30 bombings, 35 churches burned, 80 people beaten and at least six murders. Three of those murders are the focus of <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s new movie, `` Mississippi Burning,'' a fictionalized account of the slaying of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>. The story of that racially explosive summer when <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, members of CORE -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, disappeared and were killed is told through the eyes of two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents, portrayed by <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> DaFoe </PERSON>. This was the intention of screenwriter <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerolmo </PERSON> who thought the case was a `` good story'' that would be interesting to tell from the perspective of the investigators. `` I never understood this to be <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s ` civil rights' picture,'' he said `` It's an exciting story about something important. `` You see our moral failures and greatness. It allows us to see <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at its very worst and also to see people who displayed great moral courage. That's a real story.'' However, what emerges on the screen is more a detective story than a portrait of a great struggle, and that has some critics and civil rights workers miffed. The heroes are not those who at times sacrificed their lives or well-being to ensure black civil rights, but the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was unfortunate that it was so narrow in scope that it did not show one black role model that today's youth who look at the movie could remember,'' said <PERSON> Myrlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, commissioner of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, whose husband, <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON>, a field secretary for the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, was shot to death by white segregationists outside their home in 1963. `` In the state of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, not one leader was mentioned _ not Rev. -LRB- <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> -RRB- </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who gave his life so that people could register and vote, ... no -LRB- activist -RRB- <PERSON> Fannie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamer </PERSON>. Certainly no <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, who was the pioneer, the motivator of the civil rights movement in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>.'' She also took issue with <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s portrayal of the agents as compassionate -LRB- <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON> marches with mourners at <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>'s funeral -RRB-. `` I do n't remember the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents we came in contact with as being concerned with the health and welfare of the blacks,'' <PERSON> Evers </PERSON> said. `` We were more or less harassed by them.'' And she challenged the filmmakers' treatment of blacks: `` The fear that you saw in the expression of the actors who played the roles of blacks was certainly accurate during that time, but to simply show fear and no courage is very, very sad.'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, a white Southerner who worked in the Summer Project and knew the slain volunteers, talks about the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> in her book, `` Freedom Song,'' published last year by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> and Co.: `` Practically everyone working in the civil rights movement knew from firsthand experience of the duplicity of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. In many instances, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents could be seen watching a demonstration while fraternizing with sheriffs and local law officers. ... It has now become commonly accepted that some of these agents were themselves members of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>.'' Despite her misgivings, <PERSON> Evers </PERSON> said `` Mississippi Burning'' -LRB- the name of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> file on the case -RRB- was nevertheless a powerful film. `` The beatings, the lynchings, the burnings, I remember them,'' she said. `` There was a flood of remembering; I could almost reach out and touch the screen and feel the pain. But my pain was doublefold _ not only what I saw on the screen ... but also the neglect in telling the entire story.'' The film could be a contender in the upcoming Academy Award race, and has already won awards from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> for best director, best actor -LRB- <PERSON> Hackman </PERSON> -RRB- and best supporting actress -LRB- <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> McDormand </PERSON> -RRB-. It takes place in 1964, the year President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> signed the Civil Rights Act, and when <PERSON> King </PERSON> won the Nobel Prize for Peace. It also was one of the most racially violent years of the decade with riots, beatings, bombings and murders. The date is June 21: <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> are stopped by a group of white police and civilians while driving to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, to investigate the burning of a black church and some beatings. The whites are openly hostile; one sticks a gun in the driver's ear and pulls the trigger. The trio had gone to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> where only 5 percent of the black population, which made up 45 percent of the state, was registered to vote. A few days after they failed to check in with the project, as they were required to do when in the field, <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>'s charred station wagon was discovered in <LOCATION> Bogue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chitto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, 15 miles north of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Their bodies were found in a crude grave on a nearby farm on Aug. 4. The three had been shot, and <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>'s skull had been fractured from a severe beating. In December, 21 whites were arrested. Murder charges were dropped in state court, but six were later convicted in federal court for violating civil rights laws. <PERSON> Gerolmo </PERSON> interpreted some of the story himself. For instance, the identity of the person who tipped off the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> about where the bodies were buried remains unknown. In the movie, though, the informant turns out to be the deputy sheriff's wife -LRB- McDormand -RRB-. <PERSON> Gerolmo </PERSON> considered it a logical plot twist. `` The wives were often a source of information,'' he said. <PERSON> Gerolmo </PERSON> is the son of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Gero </PERSON>, a theater manager and producer. His brother, sculptor <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gero </PERSON>, is married to the actress <PERSON> Liza </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnelli </PERSON>. He was born in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and attended <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> where he taught filmmaking before going into off-Broadway theatrical production. His first movie, `` Miles From Home,'' was a box-office bomb. A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> grade schooler when <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> were killed, the incident greatly affected his way of thinking. `` It was the first time I ever considered that our country could be wrong,'' he said. `` My mother was active in the civil right movement. She marched from <LOCATION> Selma </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, and we used to discuss it around the house.'' With `` Mississippi Burning,'' he hoped to depict American life in general. Filmmakers <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Capra </PERSON> were his inspirations. `` <PERSON> Capra </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, they took on the task to say what <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is,'' <PERSON> Gerolmo </PERSON> said. `` It has something to do with taking responsibility.''
</TEXT>
