<HEAD>Veronica Hamel Is Israeli Woman in Miniseries Thriller</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the manner of `` Casablanca,'' the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` Twist of Fate'' was filmed with different endings. `` The story was very cleverly orchestrated so that it could be cut three different ways,'' said <PERSON> Veronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>, formerly of `` Hill Street Blues,'' who stars in the international thriller. `` I'm happy with the choice they made, because it was my choice. It's good that people can creatively agree and pull their resources together. I felt very good working on this, which is not always the case.'' <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON> stars with <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> in this story told against the background of World War II, the Holocaust and the founding of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The four-hour miniseries, which airs Sunday and Monday, is based on the novel `` Pursuit'' by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fish </PERSON>. `` It's a good yarn with a lot of twists,'' said <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>. `` It's not just about the Holocaust. It's about people and relationships.'' The show, as the title indicates, is indeed filled with twists. Briefly, German SS officer Helmet <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Schraeder </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON> -RRB-, fleeing Allied prosecution, has his identity changed through plastic surgery and poses as <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, a Jew -LRB- now played by Cross -RRB-. Interned in a concentration camp, he is befriended by and gains respect for his fellow prisoners. Eventually he becomes a founding father of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON> returns later in the miniseries in a dual role as <PERSON> Ben </PERSON>'s grown son who discovers the awful truth about his father and tries to bring him to justice Meanwhile, former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> colleagues learn the father's secret and attempt to blackmail him into helping with their terrorist scheme. <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON>, the Jewish woman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> marries. `` As soon as I read the script I liked the feel and texture,'' said <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>. `` I wanted to climb into her skin. I liked her passion. She was n't an appendage to a man. She had her own very strong views. `` He meets <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> when he leaves the prison camp and goes to <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>. `` She is completely unaware of his past. She has a philosophy that is a strong as her love. In fact, her philosophy comes first. She becomes a doctor, but she's not as political as <PERSON> Golda </PERSON> <PERSON> Meir </PERSON>. But at the end when I'm old, I look like a cross between <PERSON> Golda </PERSON> <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. `` I have a lot of padding to make me look thicker. That helps, having all those layers. I have to buy it first, then the audience will buy it. The first time I saw myself on the screen I started to giggle.'' The miniseries was filmed on location in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON> got a lot of action playing a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Israeli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is probably the closest I'll ever get to playing <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>,'' she said. Working in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, she said, was `` like being catapulted out of your life.'' The two-part miniseries originally was scheduled for December, but <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> decided to hold it until after the holidays. <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, was a leading model before she turned to acting. She made her stage debut in an off-off-Broadway show, `` The Big Knife.'' After several years in dinner-theater productions, she moved to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in 1975 and landed guest shots on such shows as `` The Rockford Files,'' `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' and `` Family.'' At one point she was cast in `` Charlie's Angels,'' at the time called `` Harry's Angels.'' She withdrew from the series before it went into production and the role went to <PERSON> Jaclyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>, who only recently returned from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, is now busy with her own projects. `` I'm looking for a writer for a project I will co-produce and star in,'' she said. `` It's a two-hour film for TV, and it's not a pilot. I do n't want to do a series. I've done that. It would be hard to find another as good as ` Hill Street Blues.' You have to sign for seven years and that's a long commitment. It's like a marriage. ` Hill Street' was a class act. `` I want to do some movies. But it takes years to get things off the ground. I have an idea for a feature. I'm looking for a development deal. I spend a lot of time reading scripts and books. It's hard to just sit down and read for enjoyment.'' <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON> devotes part of her time to <ORGANIZATION> Stuart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a center for sexually abused children. She is on the board of directors. She also has worked for six years with a rape treatment center.
