<HEAD>Employee Reaction Mixed, Dingell Skeptical of Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A historic plea bargain that would spare <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from a criminal indictment has incited a mixed reaction among its staff and skepticism by a key <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawmaker, who suggested the $ 650 million penalty slapped on the Wall Street giant might not go far enough. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Democrat who chairs a committee with oversight authority in the securities industry, said Thursday he would have to see details of the settlement before drawing conclusions. `` Main Street has less reason to trust Wall Street,'' he said. `` When the details of the settlement come out, we'll find out whether Main Street has reason to trust their government.'' He also said: `` I have no reason to believe that Main Street will be satisifed by anything less than the most serious punishment. Currently the public regards markets as a crap shoot and has been avoiding them like the devil avoids holy water.'' The agreement announced Wednesday would require <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record $ 650 million in fines and restitution to settle as-yet unspecified charges, most likely stemming from its relationship with <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the now-imprisoned inside trader who fingered the firm. In addition, it would require <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to provide investigators with evidence of possible wrongdoing by its high-yield bond financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and others. Although <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> senior executives expressed relief about the settlement and predicted the firm would thrive, sources familiar with internal criticism of the decision said other employees felt embittered and concerned. `` There's not going to be a mass exodus, but I think in time significant people will leave,'' said one of the sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified. `` I think suicide is a little strong, but I think it's like cutting off your arms and legs.'' The plea bargain marked a stunning turnaround for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, which had asserted its innocence since being implicated by <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> more than two years ago and had denounced him as a convicted felon and doublecrosser. Others said <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, a key target of the criminal investigation spawned by <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, felt betrayed by the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> decision, which weakens his own defense. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has maintained his innocence and has reiterated that he would fight any indictment. But the sources said that if he were indicted he would terminate his relationship with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> helped grow into one of the most aggressive and profitable firms. At the same time, the agreement took tremendous pressure off chief executive <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> and other senior managers, who had been urging colleagues to swallow their pride and settle the case so the firm could leave the protracted ordeal behind. The agreement also raised the prospect that former White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, whose <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> law practice has been advising <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> for months, would become chairman as part of a long-term recovery strategy, sources familiar with <ORGANIZATION> Baker-Drexel </ORGANIZATION> discussions said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, the onetime <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator who has been conferring in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> aides almost every other week, was visiting the firm a day before the settlement was reached, the sources said. `` Clearly the decision yesterday -LRB- Wednesday -RRB- removes one of the major obstacles,'' said one source. `` Now you can see the opportunity to talk in more detail about such a role.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s spokesman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON> declined to comment on <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s discussions or speculation about his selection as chairman `` They have continued to talk and we expect that to go forward for the next several weeks,'' <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said, `` We echo comments about discussions with him but there's nothing wider on the table.'' The settlement agreement still requires approval from senior <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials and the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which sued <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and others three months ago on civil charges of conspiring with <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> to profit on inside information, manipulate stock and commit other frauds. Sources familiar with the agreement said these other agencies must approve the agreement by mid-January. <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, declined to comment on the agreement or on the status of possible discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s spokesman, also declined to comment on any <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> discussions.
