<HEAD>Drexel Picks Up Pieces After Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After settling the nation's biggest securities fraud case, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> now faces the crucial task of retaining its clients, who include many well-known takeover strategists. The beleaguered Wall Street firm received some staunch support from a number of corporate clients Thursday, one day after it agreeing to plead guilty to six fraud charges and pay the government a record $ 650 million penalty. But some clients said privately they still needed to review whether the plea-bargaining arrangement would change their close business relationship with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't think anything at this point is that clear,'' said a spokesman for one client, which did not want to be identified. In announcing its plea agreement late Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> avoided what could have been a lengthy, costly trial that threatened to slowly destroy the firm. The government had spent two years investigating <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s relationship with <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the former stock speculator was accused of insider trading. Although the $ 650 million settlement is the largest ever in a securities fraud case, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said it may have cost more in lost business and legal fees had it continued to fight the federal charges. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> chief executive officer, said the company already has lost about $ 1.5 billion in business and paid out $ 175 million in legal expenses. The settlement, though, does not protect <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s high-yield `` junk bond'' whiz and another key target of the criminal probe <PERSON> Milken </PERS