<HEAD>Final WPPSS Trial Defendant Settles For $20 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 20 million settlement with the final defendant essentially ends the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> securities-fraud trial, but the nearly six-year-old case is far from over. The federal judge hearing the case still must decide whether to approve the out-of-court settlements reached by defendants in the class action suit, and then how to divide the roughly $ 750 million among 24,000-plus plaintiffs and attorneys. Plaintiff attorney, <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, said late Thursday in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> that the settlement pool may not be dispensed until late next year, or even later if disputes arise. The settlement by the final defendant, <ORGANIZATION> Blyth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial adviser to <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>, was announced Thursday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> still must approve 16 separate settlements reached over much of the past year. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> already has approved four settlements, reached as early as September 1987. The legal action grew from <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION>' 1983 default on $ 2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance two nuclear power plants that were abandoned before completion. The default was the biggest in the history of the municipal bond market. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> was hearing the securities fraud case in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, on a change of venue from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. The more than 100 original defendants have agreed to pay about $ 700 million to settle the case, and another $ 50 million could be collected from contested insurance claims. Plaintiff bondholders had made total claims of $ 1.6 billion. The trial, which started Sept. 7, had been expected to take up to a year. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> now is expected to dismiss the jurors, who recessed Dec. 1. In addition to approving the settlements, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> must decide how to divide the money among several classes of plaintiffs and among dozens of attorneys. Attorneys said they hoped to get the notice of settlements to the class of plaintiffs by Jan. 16, and to get approval for all of them in a March hearing. Distribution of the money will be determined after <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> holds fairness hearings, presumably in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. If all the money is in hand and there are no challenges, the award can be sent to plaintiffs all at once, said <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>. `` We hope that can be done by the end of 1989,'' he said. Some money still could be distributed if there is a dispute, with the court withholding disputed funds. Defendants in the federal lawsuit, which incorporated dozens of separate suits dating to Feb. 22, 1983, included the supply system, the 88 utilities that contracted with <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> to build the two plants, engineering firms, Wall Street bond underwriters, utility and <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> directors and <PERSON> Blyth </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastman </PERSON>. The default was on bonds <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> sold to finance construction starting in the late 1970s on its plants No. 4, at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation, and No. 5, at Satsop, west of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> abandoned the plants in 1982 because of rising construction costs and doubts about the need for the plants' power. Default occurred in July 1983 after the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that utilities participating in construction of the plants lacked authority to sign contracts with <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> guaranteeing payment even if no electricity was generated. There there has been little complaint about most of the settlements, but a proposal by the state of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to pay $ 10 million to settle any claims that might be brought against it has been criticized by plaintiffs in a state court lawsuit. Those plaintiffs claim the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state auditor failed to audit the supply system and to examine bond resolutions prior to bond sales, thus failing to protect investors. Plaintiffs are seeking the return of their full $ 2.25 billion investment, plus interest they would have received over the 30-year life of the bonds, a claim that could total $ 7 billion.
