 Nearly a continent away from Wall Street but dead center in its latest insider-trading scandal, junk bond king <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> works on an opulent avenue lined with tony boutiques and stately hotels. The decision of his employer, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to pay a record $ 650 million fine to settle criminal securities fraud charges has reportedly split the company's ranks over the fate of <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>. But there was little outward sign of that turmoil Thursday. Employees arriving for work _ the few who would acknowledge a reporter _ refused to talk about the case. Attempts to get into <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s unobtrusive offices were rebuffed by uniformed guards who staff the reception desk of the building on Rodeo Drive, the shoppers' Mecca. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has said through spokesmen that he is prepared to fight criminal charges believed pending against him. According to some who saw him socially during the many months the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> investigation has been publicly unwinding, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> appears to have retained his customary enthusiasm for business and extensive charitable interests. `` He's not a defensive-type guy,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Riordan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> attorney and investor and friend of <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s who last saw him 10 days ago at a charity event. `` He acts like nothing has happened and his whole time and effort is spent on the thing at hand,'' <PERSON> Riordan </PERSON> said. `` My guess is he's a tough guy ... I think he's going to keep doing business as usual.'' The very fact of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s presence in this enclave of the rich and famous is testament to <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s importance 