<FIRST>u f PM-Lockeheed     12-23 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lockeheed,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Investor Simmons to Boost Stake in Aerospace Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said today it had buttressed its takeover defenses following the disclosure that <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> intended to boost his holdings in the aerospace firm. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> refused to say if the changes in a 2-year-old `` poison pill'' shareholder rights plan were a direct response to <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' move. Nor would he reveal if <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, builder of the Stealth fighter and other military hardware, had discussed the investment with <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> did not immediately respond to a telephone request for comment. According to <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> filed notice under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act that he intended to boost his <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> stake beyond $ 15 million, the trigger point for the act's disclosure provisions. As of the Dec. 7 filing, <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> said it owned 375,000 of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s 59.5 million outstanding shares, or 0.63 percent. A <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> board vote to tighten the firm's takeover defenses was taken Thursday, two weeks after the filing, <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said. `` The amendment is intended to heighten the protection afforded shareholders against abusive takeover tactics,'' the company said in a news release. The revised plan allows present shareholders to buy newly issued stock at a discount if an outsider buys 20 percent or more of the common stock. Those rights can be canceled if the independent directors determine the takeover bid is in the best interest of shareholders, or if the company cancels the rights within 10 days of the time outside holdings reach 20 percent. Such poison pill plans are intended to dilute the holdings of a potential buyer, making a takeover prohibitively expensive. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, with headquarters in this <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb, has 88,000 employees in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. The nation's fourth-largest defense contractor, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> had sales of $ 11.3 billion in 1987. In the first three quarters of this year, it reported a net profit of $ 520 million on sales of $ 7.6 billion, with the profit figure boosted significantly by sale of a subsidiary. Besides the F-117A Stealth fighter, its proojects include the Trident II nuclear missile, the C-5B transport plane and work on military communications, satellites, and the Strategic Defense Initiative or Star Wars. The company also is a subcontractor for design work on <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s space station project.
