 The stock market showed a small gain today in very quiet pre-Christmas trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.50 to 2,167.86 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street. Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 812 up, 503 down and 550 unchanged. Wall Streeters were expecting a quiet day as many investors opted to get an early start on the long holiday weekend. Brokers also said money managers at investing institutions had pretty much finished their maneuvering for the year. However, stocks did attract a few nibbles from buyers as the market opened. There has been a lot of talk lately of accumulating stocks before New Year's to try to benefit from the so-called January effect. Academic researchers have published many studies about an evident tendency of stock prices to rise in the first month of the year. Whether that phenomenon will persist in 1989, of course, remains to be seen. American Brands, rumored to be a potential takeover target, jumped 8 | to 66 One unconfirmed report was that <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> was preparing to offer as much as $ 90 a share for the company's stock. <ORGANIZATION> Rexene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which said Thursday that it was engaged in talks with a possible acquirer, climbed 6 to 24 \ Gainers among the blue-chip and technology issues included <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 -LRB- at 101; <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, up -LRB- at 29 -LRB-; <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 \ at 97 \, and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION