<HEAD>Copper Posts Strong Gains On Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices surged Friday in a shortened, pre-holiday session on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as concerns about tight supplies strengthened their grip on the volatile market. On other futures markets Friday, precious metals, grains, soybeans, energy, livestock and meat futures all advanced while coffee fell slightly. Most markets closed at noon local time and will not reopen until Tuesday morning. Trading activity was uniformly light as many traders got an early start on the long Christmas weekend. Copper settled 1.1 cents to 3.2 cents higher with the spot December contract at $ 1.605 a pound and the more actively traded contract for delivery in March at $ 1.393 a pound. Prices advanced despite the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a hefty increase overnight in its warehouse stocks of copper. Comex copper stocks rose by 1,376 tons to 9,582 tons. Analysts said they expected the stocks report to put pressure on the copper market, which saw the spot price hit a record high of $ 1.6475 a pound Dec. 8 on tight-supply fears. Instead, said New York-based analyst <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, `` we closed stronger on lingering ideas that there's supply tightness that is not going to go away, especially if the economy remains resilient going into the first quarter of next year, which is normally the strongest period from a consumption standpoint.'' He said market players believed the rise in Comex stocks was temporary and that some traders were surprised the copper market was not following last year's pattern of leaping higher each day as the end of the year approached. `` But there's still a lack of production and strong demand, so while the pattern may not be repeating last year's exactly, the fundamentals are still strong,'' he said. Also on the Comex, gold settled 30 cents to 70 cents higher with February at $ 421.60 a troy ounce; silver was .20 cent to 1.1 cents higher with March at $ 6.275 a troy ounce. Soybean futures made strong gains and grain futures closed moderately higher Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors of new export business with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. After the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced a sale of 750,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn to the Soviets, confirming one of the rumors that swept the grain pits during the shortened session. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> confirmed another rumor when it announced it had targeted the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for 2 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices. And the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also said it had increased the amount of grain the Soviets could buy annually under the two nations' long-term grain agreement to 16 million metric tons from 12 million metric tons. One rumor that was not confirmed was that the Soviets had already purchased as much as 1 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean meal, analysts said. `` These rumors ... kept sellers on the sidelines,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Wheat settled 1 cent to 2 cents higher with March at $ 4.40 -LCB- a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 -RCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.84 \ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 5 cents higher with March at $ 2.37 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8 cents higher with January at $ 7.96 -LCB- a bushel Coffee futures prices slipped on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on news that a Brazilian dockworkers' strike had ended. The strike began Dec. 13. Despite the strike's end, though, analysts said near-term availability of coffee remained extremely tight, a bullish factor as cold weather in the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION> brings coffee consumption to its annual peak. Coffee settled .02 cent to 1.73 cents lower with March at $ 1.4937 a pound. Oil futures prices gained more ground on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in light, pre-holiday trading. Market sentiment has been upbeat in recent days, with many traders increasingly confident that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members will abide by a production-cutting agreement forged last month. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 19 cents higher with February at $ 16.61 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent to .79 cent higher with January at 53.14 cents gallon; unleaded gasoline was .29 cent to .72 cent higher with January at 46.86 cents a gallon. On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, live cattle settled .47 cent to .67 cent higher with February at 74.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .32 cent to .70 cent higher with January at 84.22 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .73 cent higher with February at 47.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .15 cent to .43 cent higher with February at 44.50 cents a pound.
