<HEAD>American Brands Stock Shoots Up On Unilever Takeover Rumor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was closed Friday for the Christmas holiday, but that did n't stop Wall Street from briefly sending the tobacco company's stock up 22 percent on rumors of a takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION>, the British-Dutch consumer products conglomerate. Both companies declined to discuss the rumors, citing policies against commenting on speculation. One rumor said <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> might pay as much as $ 90 a share for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>. American Brands got as high as $ 70.25 a share and was at $ 67.12 -LCB- in late trading on Wall Street, up $ 9.50, or 16 percent. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the rumor was hard to substantiate. `` I've called a number of arbitragers that are very well tuned in and nobody knows,'' he said. If it came through, a purchase by <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> would continue the trend of foreign takeovers as well as the trend of mergers in the tobacco and food businesses. In one such case, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> last week submitted to a takeover bid by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a liquor distiller. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, is a perennially mentioned takeover candidate. Earlier this year it fought off a takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> E-II </ORGANIZATION> <ORG