<HEAD>Report: Some Fares Much Higher After Northwest-Republic Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Air travelers in the Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> area paid much higher fares to some destinations in the year after the local market became dominated by one airline, according to a report published Friday In a review of 27 routes where competition was reduced by <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' 1986 merger with <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, average fares rose on 23 routes, sometimes by more than 40 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported. On all Northwest flights in and out of the Twin Cities, a separate study shows the average fare rose 18.5 percent, six times the national average, in the year after the merger, the newspaper said. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, disputes the findings. Airline officials said no broad conclusions could be drawn using isolated fare comparisons. The airline generated new data showing that Northwest flights were less expensive than similar flights from other airports by other carriers. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s study found, passengers flying to the Twin Cities saved money over those connecting to other destinations. Northwest also said that, like most airlines, it was earning thin profit margins. Many factors help explain fare increases. But <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, the architect of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline deregulation, said the broad pattern indicated in the newspaper's study of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s fares appears to conform with `` every major study with which I am familiar.'' When airline concentration increases, he said, fares tend to rise.
