<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The historic settlement of fraud charges by <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> powerhouse <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is n't expected to bring a major shakeup in the market for `` junk bonds'' pioneered and dominated by <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. Still, market players are taking a cautious, wait-and-see attitude. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> announced this past Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> had reversed itself by agreeing to admit guilt to six felonies and pay a record $ 650 million fine to settle the biggest securities fraud case in history. Expectations of a <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> settlement had grown in recent days, and the $ 180 billion market for high-risk, high-yield junk bonds was n't taken by surprise In fact, bond traders seemed relieved that the business was over after dragging on for two years and the investment firm had decided not to wage a risky fight. A `` flight to quality'' out of junk bonds and into conventional securities, which had been predicted in some quarters as a result of the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> debacle, failed to materialize. Prices of high-yield bonds were mostly little changed and even slightly higher in some cases in quiet trading. But a sort of edgy calm appeared to hang over the market as traders looked toward the new year and post-settlement prospects. `` Most people are taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, president of high-yield asset management at <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Market players are watching for further developments in the government's investigation that could prompt some junk bond traders at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to leave the firm `` This is n't over,'' said a market expert who asked not to be identified. He noted anxiety that the investigation could envelop some of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s clients, who include many well-known takeover strategists. Some of those clients said privately this past week they still needed to review whether the plea-bargaining arrangement would change their close business relationship with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. That, traders fear, could potentially affect <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to continue to sell mammoth junk bond issues, such as the one being used to help finance the $ 24.5 billion leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The market points to the <LOCATION> Nabisco </LOCATION> issue as evidence that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is still a force to be reckoned with. The other players in the junk bond market _ notably <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ might lack the clout of dominant <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> in selling huge issues, some experts suggest. `` I do n't really think we're going to see a sea change in the market,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemanski </PERSON>, director of high-yield securities research at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION>. There should n't be a major change in terms of the volume of junk issues coming to market or their prices and yields, <PERSON> Lemanski </PERSON> said. But he and other observers conceded that some segments of the market could be affected by traders leaving <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to `` mega'' issues like <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON>, junk bonds at the other end of the spectrum, worth less than $ 100 million or so, also could present a problem, analysts say. That's because the effort and expense involved in researching the companies issuing small bonds has kept all the players except <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> from bothering with them. Some of the smaller issues `` could come under pressure,'' <PERSON> Lemanski </PERSON> said.
