<HEAD>Dallas Investor Simmons Files to Boost Stake, Says No Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it had shored up its takeover defenses after <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> disclosed he might boost his stake in the aerospace company. But <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said he considered his stake in <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, builder of the Stealth fighter and other military hardware, an investment only. `` It's not that big a deal. ... We have no intention of trying to buy the whole company,'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> filed notice Dec. 7 under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act that he intended to boost his <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> stake beyond $ 15 million, the trigger point for the act's disclosure provisions. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> refused to say if changes in the company's 2-year-old `` poison pill'' shareholder rights plan were a direct response to <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' move. At the time of the filing, <ORGANIZATION> Valhi </ORGANIZATION> said it owned 375,000 of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s 59.5 million outstanding shares, or 0.63 percent. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said the filing was intended to give him leeway to buy more <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> stock with money anticipated from the planned sale of his <ORGANIZATION> Amalgamated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to a British firm. However, that $ 300 million deal fell through, he said. The investor said he had not discussed the matter with <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> officials. A <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> board vote to tighten the firm's takeover defenses was taken Thursday, two weeks after the filing, <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said. The revised plan allows present shareholders to buy newly issued stock at a discount if an outsider buys 20 percent or more of the common stock. Such poison pill plans are intended to dilute the holdings of a potential buyer, making a takeover prohibitively expensive. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, with headquarters in this <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb, has 88,000 employees in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. The nation's fourth-largest defense contractor, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> had sales of $ 11.3 billion in 1987. In the first three quarters of this year, it reported a net profit of $ 520 million on sales of $ 7.6 billion, with the profit figure boosted significantly by sale of a subsidiary. Projects include the top-secret F-117A Stealth fighter, the Trident II nuclear missile, the C-5B transport plane and work on military communications, satellites, and the Strategic Defense Initiative or Star Wars. The company also is a subcontractor for design work on <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s space station project.
