<HEAD>Mid-December Sales Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 35.9 percent leap in car sales in mid-December as overall sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks jumped 14.4 percent ahead of the same period in 1987, automakers reported Friday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> makers and foreign companies manufacturing in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> said they sold an average of 34,919 vehicles a day in the eight selling days from Dec. 11-20, up from 30,522 a day in the same period a year earlier. The Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers alone reported selling at a slightly slower 33,081 vehicle-a-day rate but that was up 15.3 percent from 28,689 a day in mid-December 1987. Sales moved at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 8.2 million vehicles, up from 7.2 million a year earlier. A year ago, with the Oct. 19 stock market crash still fresh in their minds, people were gun-shy about large purchases, said <PERSON> Jeanette </PERSON> <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON>, analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` Generally, things have been a lot more stable in these last few periods of 1988,'' she said. In the latest period, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said it sold 6,764 cars a day, up from 4,977 a day a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said its truck sales of 4,118 a day were up 21.5 percent from 3,391 a day in the year-ago period. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported the greatest increase in light-truck sales, a 28.1-percent jump to 3,177 a day from 2,481 in the 1987 period. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said its car sales reached 3,375 a day, up 20.5 percent from 2,801 a day. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its car sales rose 4.7 percent to a 10,365-a-day average, up from 9,896 a year earlier, and truck sales increased 12.7 percent to 5,282 a day from 5,144. Sales of all U.S.-made cars and light trucks reached 11,322,465 for the year to date. Sales, now in the final period of the calendar year, appeared unlikely to approach the record 16.3 million of 1986, second-best 15.7 million of 1985 or third-best 15.4 million of 1978. `` I do n't see a real kick in sales here at the end of December,'' <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON> said. `` But it's a good year. Everybody will take it.''
